			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2015</a> paper:</span><br><i>Modular capture avoidance for program transformations</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/NicoRitschel.html">Nico Ritschel</a>, <a href="../profile/SebastianErdweg.html">Sebastian Erdweg</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/2814251.2814260">10.1145/2814251.2814260</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3b.html"><span class="tagM">T3B: Transformation Languages</span></a><ul><li> The core topic is program transformation/refactoring and preventing incorrect transformations due to variable capture.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagL">T5D: Formal Methods</span></a><ul><li> Capture avoidance is treated with principled correctness criteria that go beyond ad-hoc implementation.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> It proposes a modular approach for composing transformation components without introducing capture.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagL">T2B: Evolution</span></a><ul><li> The setting includes refactorings and transformations used in maintenance and evolution workflows.
</li></ul></li></ul>
